Here's a minimal API endpoint that handles multipart form uploads with multiple images and a description:

```csharp
// Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart form with a 50 MB limit
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024
    });

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images");

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No image files provided.");

    var savedFiles = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var savePath = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(savePath);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

        savedFiles.Add(savePath);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new
    {
        Description = description,
        FileCount = savedFiles.Count,
        Paths = savedFiles
    });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();   // required for minimal APIs accepting form data without a token

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** — `MaxRequestBodySize` must be raised; the default is ~28 MB.
- **`FormOptions.MultipartBodyLengthLimit`** — independently caps the multipart body.
- **`form.Files.GetFiles("images")`** — pulls all files submitted under the `images` field name.
- **`DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed when there's no anti-forgery token (e.g., API clients).

**Example `curl` call:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=Vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```

If you prefer a strongly-typed model instead of manual form reading, you can bind directly:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload-typed", async ([FromForm] UploadRequest req) =>
{
    // req.Description and req.Images are already bound
    return Results.Ok(new { req.Description, Count = req.Images.Count });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();

public record UploadRequest(string Description, IReadOnlyList<IFormFile> Images);
```
